{"title": "Chive | Edible Herb, Allium Schoenoprasum, Culinary Uses", "author": "The Editors", "url": "https://www.britannica.com/plant/chive", "hostname": "britannica.com", "description": "Chive, (Allium schoenoprasum), small perennial plant of the amaryllis family (Amaryllidaceae), related to the onion. Chives are grown as ornamentals for their attractive flowers and as a potherb for their flavourful leaves. The leaves can be used fresh or dried and are a common seasoning for eggs,", "sitename": "Encyclopedia Britannica", "date": "1998-07-20", "id": null, "license": null, "body": null, "comments": "", "commentsbody": null, "raw_text": null, "text": "[References & Edit History](https://www.britannica.com/plant/chive/additional-info) [Related Topics](/facts/chive) [Arts & Culture](/Arts-Culture)\nchive\nOur editors will review what you\u2019ve submitted and determine whether to revise the article.\n[University of Wisconsin-Madison - Wisconsin Horticulture - Chives, Allium schoenoprasum](https://hort.extension.wisc.edu/articles/chives-allium-schoenoprasum/) [PlantVillage - Chive](https://plantvillage.psu.edu/topics/chives/infos) [WebMD - Health Benefits of Chives](https://www.webmd.com/diet/health-benefits-chives) [North Carolina Extension Gardener Plant Toolbox - Chive](https://plants.ces.ncsu.edu/plants/allium-schoenoprasum/) [Royal Horticultural Society - How to grow Chives](https://www.rhs.org.uk/herbs/chives/grow-your-own) [University of Minnesota Extension - Growing chives in home gardens](https://extension.umn.edu/vegetables/growing-chives) [Arts & Culture](/Arts-Culture)\nchive, (Allium schoenoprasum), small\n[perennial](https://www.britannica.com/science/perennial) [plant](https://www.britannica.com/plant/plant) of the amaryllis family ( [Amaryllidaceae](https://www.britannica.com/plant/Amaryllidaceae)), related to the [onion](https://www.britannica.com/plant/onion-plant). Chives are grown as ornamentals for their attractive flowers and as a potherb for their flavourful leaves. The leaves can be used fresh or dried and are a common seasoning for eggs, soups, salads, and vegetables.\nChives bear small white elongated\n[bulbs](https://www.britannica.com/science/bulb) and thin tubular [leaves](https://www.britannica.com/science/leaf-plant-anatomy), which grow in clumps. Dense spherical umbels of bluish or lilac [flowers](https://www.britannica.com/science/flower) rise above the foliage. They characteristically produce only a few [seeds](https://www.britannica.com/science/seed-plant-reproductive-part). Chives may be [propagated](https://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/propagated) by planting seeds but are [cultivated](https://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/cultivated) more commonly by dividing the clumps and planting the tiny bulbs. [\nBritannica Quiz\nPlants: From Cute to Carnivorous\n](/quiz/plants-from-cute-to-carnivorous) [Melissa Petruzzello](/editor/Melissa-Petruzzello/9400228).", "language": null, "image": "https://cdn.britannica.com/40/142140-050-E6AD9A8B/Chives.jpg", "pagetype": "ARTICLE", "links": ["/", "/", "https://subscription.britannica.com/subscribe?partnerCode=BP_GN_NAC_EUR", "https://premium.britannica.com/premium-membership/?utm_source=premium&utm_medium=global-nav-mobile&utm_campaign=evergreen", "/", "/quiz/browse", "/History-Society", "/Science-Tech", "/Biographies", "/Animals-Nature", "/Geography-Travel", "/Arts-Culture", "/money", "/videos", "/on-this-day", "/one-good-fact", "/dictionary", "/new-articles", "/History-Society", "/browse/Lifestyles-Social-Issues", "/browse/Philosophy-Religion", "/browse/Politics-Law-Government", "/browse/World-History", "/Science-Tech", "/browse/Health-Medicine", "/browse/Science", "/browse/Technology", "/Biographies", "/browse/biographies", "/Animals-Nature", "/browse/Birds-Reptiles-Vertebrates", "/browse/Bugs-Mollusks-Invertebrates", "/browse/Environment", "/browse/Fossil-Geologic-Time", "/browse/Mammals", "/browse/Plants", "/Geography-Travel", "/browse/Geograph